<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,1878,2013]" box="[199,1204,1986,2013]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,268,1986,2012]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Mine.</emphasis>
Two larvae feed together in one blotch mine. Pupation takes place within the mine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,150,899]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,150,176]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[344,479,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–83" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[162,1402,194,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-18@30.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 75–83. Figures 75–77: Cerodontha (C.) phragmitophila Hering; 75–76: posterior segments of puparium; 75: lateral view; 76: posterior view. 77: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 78–80: C. (Butomomyza) gibbifera spec. nov.; 78–79: posterior segments of puparium; 78: lateral view; 79: posterior view. 80: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 81–83: Cerodontha (Poemyza) spencerae Zlobin; 81: mine in Elymus repens leaf; 82–83: posterior segments of puparium; 82: lateral view; 83: posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158619/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figs. 75–77</figureCitation>
) Yellowish-orange, glossy, 
<quantity box="[791,877,150,177]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
long, with weak segmentation. The surface of all segments except the last two is quite smooth except for narrow spine bands; last two segments wrinkled. Posterior spiracles set on stout protuberances that are entirely separate; brown, fan-shaped, with up to twenty sessile bulbs arranged in irregular group. Anal plate slightly protruding above the surface of the puparium viewed from the side and directed ventro-posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,150,899]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,547,330,356]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Cephalopharyngeal skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[562,658,330,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 383–392" captionStartId="105.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[168,1432,193,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-15@105.[151,1435,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURES 383–392. Figures 383–387: Calycomyza artemisiae (Kaltenbach); 383: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 384: frontal view of head; 385: head viewed from the side; 386: spermathecae; 387: proctiger. Figures 388–392: Cerodontha (C.) phragmitophila Hering; 388: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 389: frontal view of head; 390: head viewed from the side; 391: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 392: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158754/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 388</figureCitation>
) Right mouthhook larger than the left, both with sharp abducted portion directed ventrally. Each mouthhook bears two accessory teeth. Intermediate sclerite long, narrow, 1.75× as long as height of left mouthhook. The mouthhook, intermediate sclerite and anterior portion of the pharyngeal sclerite are strongly sclerotized, dorsal and ventral cornua are much less so. Indentation index 77. See also in Nowakowski (1956: 
<figureCitation box="[231,329,474,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 176–184" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[164,1419,197,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-18@64.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 176–184. Figures 176–180: Phytomyza abdominalis Zetterstedt; 176: mine in Hepatica nobilis leaf; 177: larva viewed from the side; 178: puparium viewed from the side; 179: anterior segments of puparium (anterior view); 180: posterior segments of puparium (posterior view). Figures 181–184: Phytomyza aquilegiae Hardy; 181: mines in Aquilegia hybr. leaf; 182: empty puparium viewed from the side; 183: posterior segments of puparium (posterior view). 184: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158661/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 183</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,150,899]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,359,510,536]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Female head.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[376,542,510,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 383–392" captionStartId="105.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[168,1432,193,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-15@105.[151,1435,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURES 383–392. Figures 383–387: Calycomyza artemisiae (Kaltenbach); 383: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 384: frontal view of head; 385: head viewed from the side; 386: spermathecae; 387: proctiger. Figures 388–392: Cerodontha (C.) phragmitophila Hering; 388: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 389: frontal view of head; 390: head viewed from the side; 391: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 392: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158754/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figs. 389, 390</figureCitation>
) Yellow, with only oc tr, pped and arista black; pped with finger-like abducted anterodorsal process; 2 orb s, 1 fr s, lunule lunule narrow, higher than a semicircle, reaching the level between fr s and the anterior orb s.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,150,899]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,618,644]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Female thorax.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[393,488,618,644]" captionStart="FIGURES 383–392" captionStartId="105.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[168,1432,193,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-15@105.[151,1435,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURES 383–392. Figures 383–387: Calycomyza artemisiae (Kaltenbach); 383: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 384: frontal view of head; 385: head viewed from the side; 386: spermathecae; 387: proctiger. Figures 388–392: Cerodontha (C.) phragmitophila Hering; 388: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 389: frontal view of head; 390: head viewed from the side; 391: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 392: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158754/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 391</figureCitation>
) Bicolor, yellow and black: presutular area of sct almost black, postsutular area black only laterally, area between dc s yellow. Sctl black laterally, with ds sctl s on black ground and ap sct s on yellow ground.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,150,899]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,404,726,752]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[420,518,726,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 383–392" captionStartId="105.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[168,1432,193,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-15@105.[151,1435,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURES 383–392. Figures 383–387: Calycomyza artemisiae (Kaltenbach); 383: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 384: frontal view of head; 385: head viewed from the side; 386: spermathecae; 387: proctiger. Figures 388–392: Cerodontha (C.) phragmitophila Hering; 388: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 389: frontal view of head; 390: head viewed from the side; 391: dorsal view showing head, scutum and scutellum; 392: spermatheca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158754/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 392</figureCitation>
) Spermathecae equal in size, brown, spherical and flattened basally, with narrow rim-shaped basal collar.
</paragraph>
